different between rhel 7 , 8 , 9

1. Core System & Performance
RHEL 7 
Kernel Version	    3.10
Default Filesystem	XFS
Package Manager	    yum
Architecture	      x86_64

RHEL 8 
Kernel Version	    4.18
Default Filesystem	XFS(improved)
Package Manager	    dnf (labeled as yum 4)
Architecture	      x86_64-v1

RHEL 9
Kernel Version	    5.14
Default Filesystem	XFS (with Direct Access/DAX)
Package Manager	    dnf (faster, optimized)
Architecture	      x86_64-v2 (Req. newer CPUs)

2. Software Management (The Biggest Change)
RHEL 7: Used a "monolithic" approach. If you wanted a newer version of Python or PHP, you often had to use "Software Collections" (SCL), which was clunky.
RHEL 8: Introduced Application Streams (AppStreams). This allows you to install multiple versions of the same software (e.g., Python 3.6 vs 3.9) on the same OS without conflicts.
RHEL 9: Refined AppStreams. It removed many legacy "compat" libraries to make the OS smaller and faster.

3. Security & Networking
RHEL 7: Used iptables for firewall management and supported older encryption (TLS 1.0).
RHEL 8: Replaced iptables with nftables as the default filtering framework. It also introduced System-wide Crypto Policies (e.g., setting the whole system to "FUTURE" or "LEGACY" security levels).
RHEL 9: Disables SSH root login with password by default (requires keys). It also removes support for older, insecure algorithms like SHA-1 for digital signatures

4. Management Tools
RHEL 7: Mostly managed via Command Line Interface (CLI).
RHEL 8: Introduced the Cockpit Web Console as the standard GUI for server management (Storage, Networking, Logs).
RHEL 9: Cockpit is even more integrated, allowing for Kernel Live Patching and sophisticated performance metrics directly from the web browser.

5. Programming Languages (Default)
RHEL 7: Python 2.7 (Legacy).
RHEL 8: Python 3.6 (Standard), but 2.7 was still available.
RHEL 9: Python 3.9 is the default; Python 2.7 is completely removed.

Summary: Which one to use?
RHEL 7: Avoid. It reached End of Maintenance in June 2024.
RHEL 8: Best for stability and compatibility with "older" enterprise apps. Supported until 2029.
RHEL 9: Best for new deployments, cloud-native apps (containers), and the highest security standards. Supported until 2032.

Upgrading an existing RHEL server is primarily done via an in-place upgrade using the official Leapp utility. This tool automates the replacement of the operating system while preserving your data and configurations.

Critical Limitations & Upgrade Path
Sequential Upgrades: You cannot skip major versions (e.g., jumping directly from RHEL 7 to RHEL 9). You must first upgrade RHEL 7 to RHEL 8, then RHEL 8 to RHEL 9.
Supported Source: To start the upgrade, your system must be on the latest minor release of the current major version (e.g., RHEL 7.9 for a RHEL 8 upgrade).
Disk Encryption: Leapp does not currently support systems with whole-disk encryption (LUKS). 

The Upgrade Workflow
Preparation & Backup:
Perform a full system backup or take a VM snapshot.
Ensure at least 5 GB of free space in the /var filesystem.
Disable configuration management tools like Puppet, Salt, or Chef.
Install the Leapp Tool:
Enable the required "extras" repository and install the package:
sudo yum install leapp-upgrade

Pre-Upgrade Assessment:
Run the check to identify "inhibitors" (issues that will break the upgrade):

sudo leapp preupgrade --target <target_version>

Review the report generated at /var/log/leapp/leapp-report.txt. You must resolve all "Inhibitor" level risks before the actual upgrade can proceed.

Execute the Upgrade:
Once the pre-check is clean, start the upgrade:
sudo leapp upgrade --target <target_version>
sudo reboot

The system will reboot into a special RAM disk environment to perform the package swaps.
Post-Upgrade Verification:
Verify the new version: cat /etc/redhat-release.
Re-enable security policies (like SELinux if it was set to permissive) and configuration management

Would you like the exact list of inhibitor fixes commonly found when moving from RHEL 7 to RHEL 8?

To move forward with the upgrade, you must resolve these common "Inhibitors" found in the leapp-report.txt. If these aren't fixed, the upgrade process will intentionally block itself to prevent system corruption.
1. The Answerfile (Most Common)
Leapp requires you to confirm that you have acknowledged the removal of the PAM PKCS#11 module.
Fix: Run this command to "answer" the prompt:

sudo leapp answer --section remove_pam_pkcs11_module_check.confirm=True

2. PermitRootLogin (SSH)
RHEL 8 changes how the Root user logs in via SSH. You must explicitly set a configuration for it.
Fix: Edit /etc/ssh/sshd_config and ensure the line PermitRootLogin is set to either yes or prohibit-password. Then restart the service:

sudo systemctl restart sshd

3. Unsupported Kernel Modules
RHEL 8 dropped support for many older hardware drivers (like some older RAID controllers or floppy drives).
Fix: If the report lists a module (e.g., floppy or pata_acpi), you must unload it:

sudo modprobe -r module_name

Note: If your boot disk relies on a dropped driver, you cannot perform an in-place upgrade.

4. Multiple Kernel Versions
Leapp requires the system to be running the latest RHEL 7.9 kernel and have no old kernels interfering.
Fix: Update your system and reboot into the newest kernel before starting

sudo yum update -y
sudo reboot

5. Missing GPG Keys
Since you are upgrading without a subscription, Leapp may complain about missing signatures for the new RHEL 8 packages.
Fix: Import the RHEL 8 GPG key manually:

sudo rpm --import /etc/pki/rpm-gpg/RPM-GPG-KEY-redhat-release

6. Disc Space in /var/lib/leapp
The upgrade downloads several gigabytes of data to /var/lib/leapp.
Fix: Ensure you have at least 5GB of free space in /var. You can check this with df -h /var.

After upgrading RHEL without a subscription, you must manually point the package manager (dnf or yum) to the installation media to install or update software.

1. Mount the Installation Media 
First, create a mount point and mount your RHEL ISO file: 

sudo mkdir -p /mnt/disc
sudo mount -o loop /path/to/rhel-dvd.iso /mnt/disc

(Note: Replace /path/to/rhel-dvd.iso with the actual path to your downloaded RHEL 8 or 9 ISO.)

2. Create the Local Repo File
Create a new configuration file in the /etc/yum.repos.d/ directory. You can name it local.repo. 

sudo vi /etc/yum.repos.d/local.repo

3. Add the Repository Syntax 
Paste the following configuration into the file. RHEL 8 and 9 require two separate sections: BaseOS for core system packages and AppStream for applications. 
For RHEL 8/9:


ini
[BaseOS]
name=RHEL BaseOS
metadata_expire=-1
enabled=1
gpgcheck=1
baseurl=file:///mnt/disc/BaseOS/
gpgkey=file:///etc/pki/rpm-gpg/RPM-GPG-KEY-redhat-release

[AppStream]
name=RHEL AppStream
metadata_expire=-1
enabled=1
gpgcheck=1
baseurl=file:///mnt/disc/AppStream/
gpgkey=file:///etc/pki/rpm-gpg/RPM-GPG-KEY-redhat-release

(If you encounter GPG errors, you can set gpgcheck=0 temporarily to bypass signature verification.)

4. Refresh the Package Cache 
Clear the old cache and verify that the new local repositories are active: 

sudo dnf clean all
sudo dnf repolist

You should now see BaseOS and AppStream listed in the output, allowing you to install packages normally

Pro Tip: To prevent the "This system is not registered" warning from appearing every time you run a command, edit /etc/yum/pluginconf.d/subscription-manager.conf and change enabled=1 to enabled=0

To make the mount persist after a reboot, you need to add it to the /etc/fstab file. This tells the system to automatically mount the ISO or disk every time it starts up.
Step 1: Get the Path or UUID
If you are using a physical DVD or a virtual drive (like in VMware/VirtualBox), identify the device name:

lsblk

(Commonly it is /dev/sr0 or /dev/cdrom.)

Step 2: Edit the fstab File
Open the file with root privileges

sudo vi /etc/fstab

Step 3: Add the Entry
Add one of the following lines at the bottom of the file depending on your setup:
Option A: For a physical DVD/Virtual Drive

/dev/sr0   /mnt/disc   iso9660   defaults,ro   0 0

Option B: For a stored ISO file (Loop Mount)

/path/to/rhel-dvd.iso   /mnt/disc   iso9660   loop,ro   0 0

(Replace /path/to/rhel-dvd.iso with your actual file path.)


Step 4: Test the Configuration
Before rebooting, test the entry to ensure there are no syntax errors (an error in fstab can prevent the system from booting):
Unmount the current manual mount: sudo umount /mnt/disc
Run the auto-mount command: sudo mount -a
Verify it worked: ls /mnt/disc
If you see the BaseOS and AppStream folders, your configuration is correct and will survive a reboot.

